ession state, and then feeds that combined prompt to the model.</em></figca=
ption></figure></div><p></p><p>The main difference from section 1 is that s=
ection 1 was about gathering repo facts. Here, we are now interested in pac=
kaging and caching those facts efficiently for repeated model calls.</p><p>=
The =E2=80=9Cstable=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CStable prompt prefix=E2=80=9D means t=
hat the information contained there doesn=E2=80=99t change too much. It usu=
ally  contains the general instructions, tool descriptions, and the workspa=
ce summary. We don=E2=80=99t want to waste compute on rebuilding it from sc=
ratch in each interaction if nothing important has changed.</p><p>The other=
 components are updated more frequently (usually each turn). This includes =
short-term memory, the recent transcript, and the newest user request.</p><=
p>In short, the caching aspect for the =E2=80=9CStable prompt prefix=E2=80=
=9D is simply that a smart runtime tries to reuse that part.</p><h2 class=
